                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: A Push to Divest Stakes in Gun Makers</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-12-08T11:45:44+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 8, 2015 6:45 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 8, 2015 6:45 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/morning-agenda-a-push-to-divest-stakes-in-gun-makers/" data-title="Morning Agenda: A Push to Divest Stakes in Gun Makers" data-description="Keurig to be Sold for $13.9 Billion | F.T.C. Sues to Block Staples-Office Depot Deal | Criticism of Federal Reserve Gains Ground">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A PUSH TO DIVEST STAKES IN GUN MAKERS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> You probably own a stake in a gun manufacturer, whether you know it or not, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/business/dealbook/gun-shares-have-done-well-but-divestment-push-grows.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column.</a> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Anyone in a 401(k) plan</b> managed by Vanguard, BlackRock, Fidelity or just about any other mutual fund group is likely to own shares in the three publicly traded gun makers: Smith &#038; Wesson, Sturm, Ruger &#038; Company, and the Olin Corporation. So is anyone who owns any of the broad index funds or target-date retirement funds. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But there is a growing movement to divest stakes in the gun and ammunition industry. For example, the Campaign to Unload has set up a website that allows users to see if they have <b>financial exposure to gun manufacturers through their retirement plans</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Letitia James, New York Cityâs public advocate, has tried to pressure TD Bank, which provided $280 million in financing to Smith &#038; Wesson, into cutting its ties. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Efforts to <b>prevent banks and financial companies from lending money</b> have been more effective than campaigns seeking divestments. Several advocacy groups successfully ended the practice of mountaintop removal of coal in Appalachia by pressuring banks to choke off funding. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Public pension funds invested in Cerberus had already called on it to <b>sell the gun manufacturer Remington Outdoor</b>. It tried, but the auction was unsuccessful and it maintained ownership, while allowing investors to sell their stake. Last spring, it bought out investors, but maintained ownership of the company, telling investors it would be unfair to sell the company at a huge loss for investors who did not have a problem with owning a gun maker. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last week, Stop Handgun Violence, a gun control organization, looked to use financial levers to increase the pressure. It urged Americans to boycott all <b>companies owned by Cerberus</b>, including Shawâs, Star Market and Safeway. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cerberus declined to comment on this, but it did say, after Sandy Hook, âIt is not our role to take positions or attempt to shape or influence the gun policy debate.â <b>That stance should not be the default position on Wall Street</b>, Mr. Sorkin writes. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>KEURIG TO BE SOLD FOR $13.9 BILLION</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A billionaire European family went on a caffeine-fueled spending spree with the $13.9 billion acquisition of <b>Keurig Green Mountain</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/business/dealbook/keurig-green-mountain-to-be-bought-for-13-9-billion.html?ref=dealbook">Leslie Picker and Stephanie Strom report in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The JAB Holding Company, the investment arm of the Reimann family who are heirs to the German consumer goods company, Joh. A. Benckiser GmbH, offered a premium of 78 percent in its all-cash deal. A JAB-led investor group will buy Keurig for $92 a share. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">JAB, which owns controlling stakes in Jacobs Douwe Egberts and Peetâs Coffee &#038; Tea, has been on a <b>quest to dominate the coffee industry</b> and Keurig has faced sluggish sales, but still dominates the market for single-serve coffee in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some have compared JABâs push to buy up coffee businesses to <b>3G Capitalâs or Anheuser Busch InBevâs strategies</b> of consolidation. But deep and patient family pockets arenât the only thing JAB has in common with 3G, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/business/dealbook/keurig-green-mountain-gets-help-from-new-kind-of-deal-maker.html?&#038;moduleDetail=section-news-4&#038;action=click&#038;contentCollection=DealBook&#038;region=Footer&#038;module=MoreInSection&#038;version=WhatsNext&#038;contentID=WhatsNext&#038;pgtype=article">Kevin Allison writes in Breakingviews.</a> âIt also has serious industry expertise in the form of its chairman, Bart Becht, the former Reckitt Benckiser boss.â Although JAB owns stakes in Coty and Jimmy Choo, it is eyeing the huge opportunities in coffee industry. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">New coffee businesses spring up regularly in the United States and new ways of making coffee, like cold brew, continue to make it attractive to consumers. <b>Boutique coffee businesses have already been cashing in.</b> La Colombe recently sold a stake to the founder of Chobani. Peetâs has taken aim at Starbucks, taking control of Stumptown and buying a stake in Intelligentsia Coffee along the way. It now has an opportunity to get its coffee brands into the single-serve coffee market. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stakes are raised for Nespresso, which has dominated the high end for single-serve coffee. The deal also <b>changes the game for Starbucks</b>, which had allied with Keurig until it started its own single-serve coffee machine, but continued to make Keurig-compatible pods. Keurig needed Starbucks coffee pods too much to drop the brand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Keurig shares increased 72 percent to $88.89 on Monday, after a roller-coaster year during which the stock price ranged from $17.49 to $157.10. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>F.T.C. SUES TO BLOCK STAPLES-OFFICE DEPOT DEAL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Federal Trade Commission filed to block the planned $6.3 billion merger of the two office supply companies, saying that it would <b>significantly reduce competition in the market</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/business/dealbook/ftc-sues-to-block-staples-office-depot-deal.html?ref=dealbook">Liz Moyer reports in DealBook.</a> The suit seeks a temporary restraining order to hold up the deal between Staples and Office Depot pending an administrative trial scheduled to begin in May. The Canadian Competition Bureau also filed to block the transaction. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Staples and Office Depot are often the top two bidders for the business of large companies, the regulator said in an administrative suit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two companies pushed back, arguing that the regulatorâs decision was <b>based on a flawed analysis</b>. They said they would pursue legal options to complete the merger. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Both the companiesâ shares dropped after the F.T.C. announcement â Staples was down 8 percent and Office Depot fell 15 percent. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The F.T.C. had already <b>blocked previous plans for a merger in 1997</b>, and this deal was expected to be closely scrutinized. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>House Financial Services Committee</b> holds a hearing on âOversight of the Financial Stability Oversight Councilâ at 10 a.m. The Senate Judiciary Subcommittee on Antitrust, Competition Policy and Consumer Rights will hold a hearing on the <b>Anheuser-Busch InBev and SABMiller merger</b> at 10 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CRITICISM OF FEDERAL RESERVE GAINS GROUND</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> HÃ©lÃ¨ne Rey, a professor at the London Business School, has argued that the Federal Reserveâs policies have such great impact on global markets that  <b>emerging markets have been powerless to cope with the investment flows</b> pouring in and out of their economies. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Her research <b>prompted Ben Bernanke</b> to vigorously defend the central bankâs aggressive moves, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/business/dealbook/economists-criticism-of-federal-reserve-policies-gains-ground.html?ref=dealbook">Landon Thomas Jr. writes in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Rey has recommended that policy makers put in place <b>regulations that reduce the intensity and speculative fervor of these flows</b> â capital controls in some markets and rules punishing short-term trading by investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She is not the first economist to contend that volatile capital flows may be harmful.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Ms. Rey has also highlighted how new <b>exchange rate policies intended to help handle these money streams have not worked</b>. In previous market crises, countries often got into trouble because their exchange rates were tied to the dollar. The I.M.F. and most economists advised these countries to insulate themselves by letting their currencies float freely. Ms. Rey found that countries like Brazil, Turkey and South Africa remained just as exposed to the whipsaw effect of rate-driven capital flows.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Her research <b>questions the idea</b> that the free flow of capital into and out of emerging economies is a force for good that should be encouraged. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fed governors surprised many this fall by not raising rates, citing the impact that Chinaâs currency devaluation would have on the fragile emerging markets. With all signs pointing to a rate increase this month and <b>fears about emerging markets</b> being affected by investors fleeing for higher yield prospects in the United States, Ms. Reyâs research has become particularly relevant. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
